rComments: I really enjoyed his class. it was very interesting and not difficult if you study the lectures and go through the readings he posts weekly. There was only one assignment due at the end of the semester, only worth 5% of the grade. The rest is midterms and final. I would really recommend this class, it was one of my favorite classes i took.
There was kind of a textbook, but most of the questions from readings on the tests were from the online readings he posted. Sometimes he's a bit quiet or mumbles but overall he's a decent lecturer.

Interesting lectures with a lot of videos. Don't be late to his lectures because it really annoys him. Your grade is literally weighted on two midterms and the exam so I recommend going to lecture and reading any assigned readings. A lot to memorize. Overall, Chambers is a good prof that got me interested into the psychology of human communication.

Great professor, incredibly knowledgable on the topic and very well spoken. Powerpoints are well structured. Might be considered dry if you are not interested in the topic of language and communication. He reuses questions of old tests so it helps for the test. I would 100% retake the course and will continue taking courses that he teaches.
Incredibly boring and dry course. He spent 1/3 of each lecture showing us videos. His tests are okay, and he doesn't really use a textbook, so it's average, he's just really boring and monotone.

Wasn't super interested in taking this course at first, but Craig knows what he's talking about, and made it more interesting than other profs would have. He loves to talk about studies in class, so make sure you know those. Tests involve mostly lectures, but certain definitions and concepts from the book are used. Pretty good class!

He explains concepts well, his slides are sometimes confusing so you must attend the lectures to do well. The tests weren't easy but very fair. He is a creature of habit so use past tests and attempt all the short answers on past tests, the MC is very easy.

The lectures, despite being 6-9 at night, were interesting. He uses a lot of examples & interesting videos to explain things. If you know all the studies he talks about in detail and use past tests you are bound to do really well in class. You have to attend the lectures if you want to pass, his slides are not as detailed as your answers should be.

Good prof. Explains concepts clearly (although it's all on the slides, so don't need to attend class). Tests are very fair, almost easy. He uses a lot of examples to make the material more relevant (but still kind of dry). Oh, and he's very eloquent and well-spoken! Good prof overall

This professor is unbelievably dry. Listening to his thin nasal drone in my seat for three hours I think of ways to kill myself. He presents facts  without flair, speaking slowly and stopping constantly, cutting the flow of the lecture and deadening the atmosphere. The most unbearable lecturer I have had in two years.

Amazing, one of my favourite profs! He makes lectures interesting by pulling a lot of real world examples -videos, pictures, etc. His tests are very fair, you'll do fine if you do the readings and listen in class. He explains everything really well, and is speedy in replying to emails. Despite the 3 hour lecture til 9 pm, my favourite class.
He's a great prof! explains things very clearly with examples. Very enthusiastic. Its  a pleasure to be in his lectures. And tests are very fair and straightforward.
hes fair and decent. plus he's elegant and his walk is so adorable. i would take his class just to watch him walk and talk. its so worth half a thousand dollars.
He's really helpful! He speaks clearly and he actually cares.

Chambers can be a great prof if you learn his style. PSY274 i got a 69. PSY376 I'm heading towards an 85+. He is very monotone, but very clear. Take notes as an ADDITION to his lecture slides, and read the text thoroughly. MC is simple, and short answers are based on theories outlined in readings and lectures. 40% weighted first test still sucks

I think he is a very well spoken prof. He explains things and elaborates with clear examples. Some parts of the material are really dry and boring. But overall, I would recommend the course and this prof. I enjoyed it.

Overall, he knows what he's talking about.  Some lectures are interesting; others not.  Read assigned readings b4 going to class--DON'T EVER CRAM--it'll haunt you.  If you read, it'll reduce the note-taking.  If you don't read, take good notes.  Heavy course.  MC is easy, but short answers aren't.  A lot of thinking is involved.

well spoken, very clear. lecture notes are awesome and straight to the point. his tests are graded fairly. i might be biased though because i did well in this course cause i've heard other things about him.

WORSE class in my entire life... The lectures come off as easy stuff but 80% of the TEST is the hardest most specific examples from the text and terminology too.  He teaches okish but if you try arguing your mark because you think you explained something he backs up the TA every time even if you use his in class examples BLAH

OMG, attended all his lectures, reviewed lecture notes as well as read the DREADFULLY boring textbook and still did not do well, YOU have to know his lectures INSIDE out as well as the textbook material, extremely boring class
He comes across as charming, well-spoken, and down-to-earth. He is at the same time DIFFICULT. You're going to have to know his lectures like the back of your hand if you want to get a good mark.

Well-groomed, exceptionaly well-spoken, and has a remarkable capability to explain concepts in the most interesting and memorable manner. I definitely recommend taking a class with him. One of the few UofT professors who actually can teach. Thanks Prof. Chambers! :)
